nough even with the omission. Looking at the source, I notice the codeSelect tag also supports a withNoneOption attribute set to true.\n\nNow I'm reviewing the additional attributes for the code tag itself—it only accepts common attributes, and the name attribute is optional. When name is omitted, it displays all code values matching the codeId and pattern. When name is specified, it retrieves the value from the variable scope in display-only mode. The knowledge files confirm these behaviors.\n\nMoving through the verification checklist, the common attributes table covers name, codeId, pattern with its default, optionColumnName, labelPattern with its default and placeholders, and listFormat with its default and available formats, plus a note about listFormat scopes. The usage examples all check out as accurate.\n\nFor codeRadioButtons and codeCheckboxes, I'm confirming that only common attributes are added, the id attribute auto-generates in the format `nablarch_<radio|checkbox><sequence>` where the sequence starts at 1 based on appearance order in the screen, and the tabindex attribute... 見出し構造を確認しているんだけど、RST形式のドキュメントタイトルが「codeSelectタグ、codeRadiobuttonsタグ、codeCheckboxesタグ、codeタグ」で、その下に「共通属性」と「codeRadiobuttonsタグ、codeCheckboxesタグ」「codeSelectタグ」「codeタグ」という複数のセクションが続いている。共通属性のセクションの後に明示的な小見出しがないから、そこの構造を整理する必要がある。 I'm realizing the RST heading hierarchy isn't fixed by character choice—it's determined by the order they first appear in the document. So I need to recount the actual heading levels based on which underline characters show up first, not assume dashes always mean the same level. The automated check flagging 8 headings versus my count of 4-5 suggests I might be missing some nested structure or miscounting the hierarchy levels. I'm realizing the underline lengths matter too—the dashes and equals signs have different character counts, which affects how RST interprets the hierarchy. Let me reconsider the structure based on the actual lengths of each underline rather than just the character type. The structure maps to 5 sections which aligns with what I'm seeing in the source, though the automated check is flagging 8 headings—likely counting delimiter variations differently. Looking at the hints for each section, s1 covers the common attributes with references to select, radio buttons, checkboxes, and various field properties like name, ID, pattern, and column mappings.\n\nI notice s1 is missing some key placeholder names like `$NAME$`, `$SHORTNAME$`, `$OPTIONALNAME$`, and `$VALUE$` that appear in the source documentation around label formatting—these would help users find this section when asking about how to format labels. The other sections have their hints fairly well populated: s2 covers usage examples with pattern and table references, s3 focuses on the radio and checkbox implementations with their HTML attributes, and s4 specifically addresses the select component with its none-option handling.\n\nLooking at the overall structure, the knowledge file seems to capture the source material accurately without major gaps or errors. The one minor issue I spot is that the HTML output example in s3 gets truncated with ellipsis, showing only a couple of radio buttons instead of the full set of five, though this is just an abbreviation rather than a real omission since the complete example exists in the source. I'm checking whether the truncation with `...` in the output examples is actually a problem—the pattern is clear enough from the first couple of radio buttons shown, so it's acceptable for an AI-ready file. Looking at the source material more carefully, I notice the knowledge file omits a comparison to how other tags handle label output, but since the actual behavior is still documented, this feels like a minor gap rather than a real omission.\n\nThe section count discrepancy is worth investigating—the automated check flagged 5 sections versus 8 heading-like structures in the source RST file, so I need to map out what those actual sections are to see if something's genuinely missing from the knowledge file. I'm realizing the distinction between RST section headings and transition markers—bare separator lines without text above them are treated as horizontal rules, not actual sections. Looking back at the source structure, the underlined text like `共通属性` and the tagged elements are the true headings, while the standalone `---` lines between them are just visual dividers. This explains why the automated check might be overcounting if it's treating those transition markers as section boundaries when they're not actually structural headings in RST. The HTML example in s3 truncates the radio button options with ellipsis, omitting radio3-5, though the pattern is clear enough. I've confirmed that s4 properly preserves the reference to the separate usage examples file, so that's accurate. The file looks clean overall—just that minor code example truncation to note. Looking at the s3 section more carefully, I notice the knowledge file cuts off mid-sentence when describing the id attribute format for labels — it says the format is `nablarch_<radio|checkbox><連番>` but doesn't complete the explanation about how the numbering works within the screen. The source provides the full detail about sequential numbering starting from 1, but the knowledge file appears to be truncated there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22962,"cache_read_input_tokens":29873,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22962,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0a94756d-4e3d-435c-b8b7-0114c0618296","uuid":"4d745e92-ec13-46b6-aad4-a10129eeae17"}
